tures.Departing from tenets of modernist studies and from methods in the field of trauma and memory studies, Rizzuto contends that acute as well as chronic disruptions to imperial and national power and the legal and extra-legal responses they inspired shape the formal practices of literatures from the modernist, colonial, and postcolonial periods.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCommonwealth literature (English)xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aJustice, Administration of, in literature. 0aLiterature and societyzEnglish-speaking countries. 0aNationalism and literaturezEnglish-speaking countries. 0aPsychic trauma in literature. 0aWar in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPostcolonial Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / African.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823267842zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823267842423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823267842/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK